name: NPR
text:
Tropical Cyclone Gati has made landfall in Somalia, where it's expected to drop two years' worth of rain in the next two days. It's the first recorded instance of a hurricane-strength system hitting the country. 
https://t.co/tnf7LxAE5m

name: NPR
text: Most presidents spend their final weeks in office trying to cement their legacies. But Trump's tactics since he lost to Biden have raised alarms that he's doing damage to confidence in free and fair elections. https://t.co/vPuXoMr3On

name: NPR
text: Kasich, a 2016 Republican presidential candidate, told NPR that Biden "has clearly won this election and it is just sort of amazing to me that Republicans just keep sitting on their hands. It makes no sense." https://t.co/AVALJHaDc2

text:
Lebanon's ancient cedar trees are a source of national pride. But climate change has brought their very survival into question, as rising temperatures fuel growing threats from wildfires and insect infestations.
https://t.co/crch1tv9fX

text: A 12-year-old German pro soccer fan has been building detailed lego reconstructions of their stadiums without the help of blueprints. https://t.co/wtzXewn45M

name: NPR
text:
The late documentary photographer Mary Ellen Mark's lifelong passion was to give visibility to the invisible. As her husband, Martin Bell, puts it:

"Mary Ellen could see a story in the ordinary that you might just walk by and not even see."
https://t.co/VnF3ztrMb7
